# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: failure-mode-effects-analysis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Sometimes FMEA is extended to FMECA(failure mode, effects, and criticality analysis) with Risk Priority Numbers (RPN) to indicate criticality.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] FMEA is an inductive reasoning (forward logic) single point of failure analysis and is a core task in reliability engineering, safety engineering and quality engineering.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A successful FMEA activity helps identify potential failure modes based on experience with similar products and processes—or based on common physics of failure logic.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It is widely used in development and manufacturing industries in various phases of the product life cycle.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] *Effects analysis* refers to studying the consequences of those failures on different system levels.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Functional analyses are needed as an input to determine correct failure modes, at all system levels, both for functional FMEA or piece-part (hardware) FMEA.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] An FMEA is used to structure mitigation for risk reduction based on either reducing the severity of the failure mode or effect, or on lowering the probability of failure, or both.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The FMEA is in principle a full inductive (forward logic) analysis; however the failure probability can only be estimated or reduced by understanding the *failure mechanism*.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Hence, FMEA may include information on causes of failure (deductive analysis) to reduce the possibility of occurrence by eliminating identified *(root) causes*.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The FME(C)A is a design tool used to systematically analyze postulated component failures and identify the resultant effects on system operations.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The analysis is sometimes characterized as consisting of two sub-analyses, the first being the failure modes and effects analysis (FMEA), and the second, the criticality analysis (CA).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Successful development of an FMEA requires that the analyst include all significant failure modes for each contributing element or part in the system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] FMEAs can be performed at the system, subsystem, assembly, subassembly or part level.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The FMECA should be a living document during development of a hardware design.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It should be scheduled and completed concurrently with the design.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] If completed in a timely manner, the FMECA can help guide design decisions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The usefulness of the FMECA as a design tool and in the decision-making process is dependent on the effectiveness and timeliness with which design problems are identified.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Timeliness is probably the most important consideration.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In the extreme case, the FMECA would be of little value to the design decision process if the analysis is performed after the hardware is built.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It starts at higher functional / system level.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] An FTA may use the basic failure mode FMEA records or an effect summary as one of its inputs (the basic events).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Interface hazard analysis, human error analysis and others may be added for completion in scenario modelling.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The analysis should always be started by someone listing the functions that the design needs to fulfill.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Functions are the starting point of a well done FMEA, and using functions as baseline provides the best yield of an FMEA.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] After all, a design is only one possible solution to perform functions that need to be fulfilled.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This way an FMEA can be done on concept designs as well as detail designs, on hardware as well as software, and no matter how complex the design.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] When performing a FMECA, interfacing hardware (or software) is first considered to be operating within specification.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] After that it can be extended by consequently using one of the 5 possible failure modes of one function of the interfacing hardware as a cause of failure for the design element under review.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This gives the opportunity to make the design robust against function failure elsewhere in the system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In addition, each part failure postulated is considered to be the only failure in the system (i.e., it is a single failure analysis).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In addition to the FMEAs done on systems to evaluate the impact lower level failures have on system operation, several other FMEAs are done.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Special attention is paid to interfaces between systems and in fact at all functional interfaces.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The purpose of these FMEAs is to assure that irreversible physical and/or functional damage is not propagated across the interface as a result of failures in one of the interfacing units.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] These analyses are done to the piece part level for the circuits that directly interface with the other units.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The FMEA can be accomplished without a CA, but a CA requires that the FMEA has previously identified system level critical failures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] When both steps are done, the total process is called an FMECA.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The ground rules of each FMEA include a set of project selected procedures; the assumptions on which the analysis is based; the hardware that has been included and excluded from the analysis; and the rationale for the exclusions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The ground rules also describe the indenture level of the analysis (i.e. the level in the hierarchy of the part to the sub-system, sub-system to the system, etc.), the basic hardware status, and the criteria for system and mission success.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Every effort should be made to define all ground rules before the FMEA begins; however, the ground rules may be expanded and clarified as the analysis proceeds.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] All inputs (including software commands) to the item being analyzed are present and at nominal values.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] All consumables are present in sufficient quantities.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Major benefits derived from a properly implemented FMECA effort are as follows.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A documented uniform method of assessing potential failure mechanisms, failure modes and their impact on system operation, resulting in a list of failure modes ranked according to the seriousness of their system impact and likelihood of occurrence.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Early identification of single failure points (SFPS) and system interface problems, which may be critical to mission success and/or safety.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] They also provide a method of verifying that switching between redundant elements is not jeopardized by postulated single failures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] An effective method for evaluating the effect of proposed changes to the design and/or operational procedures on mission success and safety.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A basis for in-flight troubleshooting procedures and for locating performance monitoring and fault-detection devices.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] From the above list, early identifications of SFPS, input to the troubleshooting procedure and locating of performance monitoring / fault detection devices are probably the most important benefits of the FMECA.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In addition, the FMECA procedures are straightforward and allow orderly evaluation of the design.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Procedures for conducting FMECA were described in 1949 in US Armed Forces Military Procedures document MIL-P-1629, revised in 1980 as MIL-STD-1629A.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] By the early 1960s, contractors for the U.S.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] National Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) were using variations of FMECA or FMEA under a variety of names.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] NASA programs using FMEA variants included Apollo, Viking, Voyager, Magellan, Galileo, and Skylab.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The civil aviation industry was an early adopter of FMEA, with the Society for Automotive Engineers (SAE, an organization covering aviation and other transportation beyond just automotive, despite its name) publishing ARP926 in 1967.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] After two revisions, Aerospace Recommended Practice ARP926 has been replaced by ARP4761, which is now broadly used in civil aviation.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] During the 1970s, use of FMEA and related techniques spread to other industries.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In 1971 NASA prepared a report for the U.S.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Geological Survey recommending the use of FMEA in assessment of offshore petroleum exploration.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Environmental Protection Agency report described the application of FMEA to wastewater treatment plants.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] FMEA as application for HACCP on the Apollo Space Program moved into the food industry in general.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The automotive industry began to use FMEA by the mid 1970s.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The Ford Motor Company introduced FMEA to the automotive industry for safety and regulatory consideration after the Pinto affair.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Ford applied the same approach to processes (PFMEA) to consider potential process induced failures prior to launching production.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In 1993 the Automotive Industry Action Group (AIAG) first published an FMEA standard for the automotive industry.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The SAE first published related standard J1739 in 1994.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This standard is also now in its fourth edition.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In 2019 both method descriptions were replaced by the new AIAG / VDA FMEA handbook.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It is a harmonization of the former FMEA standards of AIAG, VDA, SAE and other method descriptions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] As of 2024, the AIAG / VDA FMEA Handbook is accepted by GM, Ford, Stellantis, Honda NA, BMW, Volkswagen Group, Mercedes-Benz Group AG (formerly Daimler AG), and Daimler Truck.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Although initially developed by the military, FMEA methodology is now extensively used in a variety of industries including semiconductor processing, food service, plastics, software, and healthcare.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Toyota has taken this one step further with its design review based on failure mode (DRBFM) approach.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The method is now supported by the American Society for Quality which provides detailed guides on applying the method.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The standard failure modes and effects analysis (FMEA) and failure modes, effects and criticality analysis (FMECA) procedures identify the product failure mechanisms, but may not model them without specialized software.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This limits their applicability to provide a meaningful input to critical procedures such as virtual qualification, root cause analysis, accelerated test programs, and to remaining life assessment.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] To overcome the shortcomings of FMEA and FMECA a failure modes, mechanisms and effect analysis (FMMEA) has often been used.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A variation of FMEA developed for functional safety applications is called Design Deviation and Mitigation Analysis (DDMA).[5] The DDMA variation adds information not normally included in a FMEA such as the automatic diagnostic mitigations, latent fault tests, and useful life.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] DDMA deletes RPN numbers as they are replaced by FMEDA results.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] For Ford specifically, these requirements had multiple-stage compliance deadlines of July and December of 2022.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The following covers some basic FMEA terminology.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The AP replaces the former risk matrix and RPN in the AIAG / VDA FMEA handbook 2019.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It makes a statement about the need for additional improvement measures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The loss of a function under stated conditions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The specific manner or way by which a failure occurs in terms of failure of the part, component, function, equipment, subsystem, or system under investigation.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Depending on the type of FMEA performed, failure mode may be described at various levels of detail.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A piece part FMEA will focus on detailed part or component failure modes (such as fully fractured axle or deformed axle, or electrical contact stuck open, stuck short, or intermittent).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A functional FMEA will focus on functional failure modes.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] These may be general (such as no function, over function, under function, intermittent function, or unintended function) or more detailed and specific to the equipment being analyzed.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A PFMEA will focus on process failure modes (such as inserting the wrong drill bit).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Defects in requirements, design, process, quality control, handling or part application, which are the underlying cause or sequence of causes that initiate a process (mechanism) that leads to a failure mode over a certain time.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] For example; "fatigue or corrosion of a structural beam" or "fretting corrosion in an electrical contact" is a failure mechanism and in itself (likely) not a failure mode.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The related failure mode (end state) is a "full fracture of structural beam" or "an open electrical contact".
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The initial cause might have been "Improper application of corrosion protection layer (paint)" and /or "(abnormal) vibration input from another (possibly failed) system".
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Immediate consequences of a failure on operation, or more generally on the needs for the customer / user that should be fulfilled by the function but now is not, or not fully, fulfilled.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] An identifier for system level and thereby item complexity.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Complexity increases as levels are closer to one.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The failure effect as it applies to the item under analysis.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The failure effect as it applies at the next higher indenture level.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The failure effect at the highest indenture level or total system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The means of detection of the failure mode by maintainer, operator or built in detection system, including estimated dormancy period (if applicable).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The likelihood of the failure occurring.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Severity (of the event) × probability (of the event occurring) × detection (probability that the event would not be detected before the user was aware of it).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Severity considers the worst potential consequence of a failure, determined by the degree of injury, property damage, system damage and/or time lost to repair the failure.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Additional info, including the proposed mitigation or actions used to lower a risk or justify a risk level or scenario.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Severely reduced aircraft deceleration on ground and side drift.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Partial loss of runway position control.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It is necessary to look at the cause of a failure mode and the likelihood of occurrence.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This can be done by analysis, calculations / FEM, looking at similar items or processes and the failure modes that have been documented for them in the past.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A failure cause is looked upon as a design weakness.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] All the potential causes for a failure mode should be identified and documented.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Examples of causes are: Human errors in handling, manufacturing induced faults, fatigue, creep, abrasive wear, erroneous algorithms, excessive voltage or improper operating conditions or use (depending on the used ground rules).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A failure mode may be given a *Probability Ranking* with a defined number of levels.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This field is also often referred to as an *Occurrence Rating*.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] For a piece part FMEA, quantitative probability may be calculated from the results of a reliability prediction analysis and the failure mode ratios from a failure mode distribution catalog, such as RAC FMD-97.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This method allows a quantitative FTA to use the FMEA results to verify that undesired events meet acceptable levels of risk.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Determine the Severity for the worst-case scenario adverse end effect (state).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It is convenient to write these effects down in terms of what the user might see or experience in terms of functional failures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Examples of these end effects are: full loss of function x, degraded performance, functions in reversed mode, too late functioning, erratic functioning, etc.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Each end effect is given a Severity number (S) from, say, I (no effect) to V (catastrophic), based on cost and/or loss of life or quality of life.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] These numbers prioritize the failure modes (together with probability and detectability).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Below a typical classification is given.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The means or method by which a failure is detected, isolated by operator and/or maintainer and the time it may take.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This is important for maintainability control (availability of the system) and it is especially important for multiple failure scenarios.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It should be made clear how the failure mode or cause can be discovered by an operator under normal system operation or if it can be discovered by the maintenance crew by some diagnostic action or automatic built in system test.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A dormancy and/or latency period may be entered.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The average time that a failure mode may be undetected may be entered if known.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] If the undetected failure allows the system to remain in a *safe* / working state, a second failure situation should be explored to determine whether or not an indication will be evident to all *operators* and what corrective action they may or should take.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This type of analysis is useful to determine how effective various test processes are at the detection of latent and dormant faults.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The method used to accomplish this involves an examination of the applicable failure modes to determine whether or not their effects are detected, and to determine the percentage of failure rate applicable to the failure modes which are detected.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The possibility that the detection means may itself fail latently should be accounted for in the coverage analysis as a limiting factor (i.e., coverage cannot be more reliable than the detection means availability).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Inclusion of the detection coverage in the FMEA can lead to each individual failure that would have been one effect category now being a separate effect category due to the detection coverage possibilities.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Another way to include detection coverage is for the FTA to conservatively assume that no holes in coverage due to latent failure in the detection method affect detection of all failures assigned to the failure effect category of concern.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The FMEA can be revised if necessary for those cases where this conservative assumption does not allow the top event probability requirements to be met.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] After these three basic steps the Risk level may be provided.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Preliminary risk levels can be selected based on a risk matrix like that shown below, based on Mil.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The higher the risk level, the more justification and mitigation is needed to provide evidence and lower the risk to an acceptable level.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] High risk should be indicated to higher level management, who are responsible for final decision-making.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] A new FMEA variation, **Design Deviation and Mitigation Analysis (DDMA)**, has been introduced.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This method adapts Functional Safety requirements to the Design FMEA process.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] This technique allows for the simultaneous collection of FMEDA information, leveraging functional safety engineering insights to streamline the FMEA.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The functional safety process largely replaces the need for traditional Risk Priority Numbers (RPN).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] To facilitate FMEDA setup, the DDMA process also incorporates descriptions of automatic diagnostics (action taken, coverage) and evaluates the effectiveness of latent fault testing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] While FMEA identifies important hazards in a system, its results may not be comprehensive and the approach has limitations.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In the healthcare context, FMEA and other risk assessment methods, including SWIFT (Structured What If Technique) and retrospective approaches, have been found to have limited validity when used in isolation.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Challenges around scoping and organisational boundaries appear to be a major factor in this lack of validity.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] If used as a top-down tool, FMEA may only identify major failure modes in a system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Fault tree analysis (FTA) is better suited for "top-down" analysis.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] When used as a bottom-up tool FMEA can augment or complement FTA and identify many more causes and failure modes resulting in top-level symptoms.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] It is not able to discover complex failure modes involving multiple failures within a subsystem, or to report expected failure intervals of particular failure modes up to the upper level subsystem or system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Additionally, the multiplication of the severity, occurrence and detection rankings may result in rank reversals, where a less serious failure mode receives a higher RPN than a more serious failure mode.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The reason for this is that the rankings are ordinal scale numbers, and multiplication is not defined for ordinal numbers.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The ordinal rankings only say that one ranking is better or worse than another, but not by how much.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] For instance, a ranking of "2" may not be twice as severe as a ranking of "1", or an "8" may not be twice as severe as a "4", but multiplication treats them as though they are.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] See Level of measurement for further discussion.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Various solutions to this problems have been proposed, e.g., the use of fuzzy logic as an alternative to classic RPN model.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] In the new AIAG / VDA FMEA handbook (2019) the RPN approach was replaced by the AP (action priority) in the Supplemental FMEA for Monitoring and System Response (FMEA-MSR) method.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The FMEA worksheet is hard to produce, hard to understand and read, as well as hard to maintain.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The use of neural network techniques to cluster and visualise failure modes were suggested starting from 2010.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] An alternative approach is to combine the traditional FMEA table with a set of bow-tie diagrams.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The diagrams provide a visualisation of the chains of cause and effect, while the FMEA table provides the detailed information about specific events.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The software FMEA focuses on failure modes that originate in the software requirements, design, code or interfaces.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The software should not be treated as a "black box" in this analysis.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Instead a listing of root causes that historically lead to software failures should be considered instead.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] The software FMEA is a design FMEA in that the goal is to identify missing, insufficient or incorrect design specifications before the code is written.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Probability is NOT computed from software failure rates for the simple reason that software failure rates measure the time between software failures of EVERY root cause as opposed to the time between a failure due to a single root cause.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Additionally, with software failures, the root causes will either be corrected or avoided when the failure occurs.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] So, time between a specific root cause has minimal value.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Medium severity failures that occur repeatedly can result in a very serious system failure.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] So the analyst must consider this when assessing severity.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Software failures aren't limited to a total loss of function.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] As per the IEEE 1633, if the software performs a function that is not correct as per the requirements, it is counted as a failure.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] Compensating provisions don't necessarily mitigate the severity of a software failure.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode-and-effects-analysis] That's because many software failures occur without warning and many cause damage before an operator can intervene.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] A part failure mode is the way in which a component failed "functionally" on the component level.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] Often a part has only a few failure modes.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] For example, a relay may fail to open or close contacts on demand.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] The failure mechanism that caused this can be of many different kinds, and often multiple factors play a role at the same time.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] They include corrosion, welding of contacts due to an abnormal electric current, return spring fatigue failure, unintended command failure, dust accumulation and blockage of mechanism, etc.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] Seldom only one cause (hazard) can be identified that creates system failures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] The real root causes can in theory in most cases be traced back to some kind of human error, e.g. design failure, operational errors, management failures, maintenance induced failures, specification failures, etc.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] A scenario is the complete identified possible sequence and combination of events, failures (failure modes), conditions, system states, leading to an end (failure) system state.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] It starts from causes (if known) leading to one particular end effect (the system failure condition).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] A failure scenario is for a system the same as the failure mechanism is for a component.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] Both result in a failure mode (state) of the system / component.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] The term is part of the engineering lexicon, especially of engineers working to test and debug products or processes.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] Carefully observing and describing failure conditions, identifying whether failures are reproducible or transient, and hypothesizing what combination of conditions and sequence of events led to failure is part of the process of fixing design flaws or improving future iterations.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] The term may be applied to mechanical systems failure.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] Some types of mechanical failure mechanisms are: excessive deflection, buckling, ductile fracture, brittle fracture, impact, creep, relaxation, thermal shock, wear, corrosion, stress corrosion cracking, and various types of fatigue.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] Each produces a different type of fracture surface, and other indicators near the fracture surface(s).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] The way the product is loaded, and the loading history are also important factors which determine the outcome.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] Of critical importance is design geometry because stress concentrations can magnify the applied load locally to very high levels, and from which cracks usually grow.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] Over time, as more is understood about a failure, the failure cause evolves from a description of symptoms and outcomes (that is, effects) to a systematic and relatively abstract model of how, when, and why the failure comes about (that is, causes).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] The more complex the product or situation, the more necessary a good understanding of its failure cause is to ensuring its proper operation (or repair).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] Cascading failures, for example, are particularly complex failure causes.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] Edge cases and corner cases are situations in which complex, unexpected, and difficult-to-debug problems often occur.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] Materials can be degraded by their environment by corrosion processes, such as rusting in the case of iron and steel.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/failure-mode] Such processes can also be affected by load in the mechanisms of stress corrosion cracking and environmental stress cracking.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The *reliability function* is theoretically defined as the probability of success.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In practice, it is calculated using different techniques, and its value ranges between 0 and 1, where 0 indicates no probability of success while 1 indicates definite success.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] This probability is estimated from detailed (physics of failure) analysis, previous data sets, or through reliability testing and reliability modeling.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability, testability, maintainability, and maintenance are often defined as a part of "reliability engineering" in reliability programs.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability often plays a vital role in the cost-effectiveness of overall systems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering deals with the prediction, prevention, and management of high levels of "lifetime" engineering uncertainty and risks of failure.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Although stochastic parameters define and affect reliability, reliability is not only achieved by mathematics and statistics.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering relates closely to quality engineering, safety engineering, and system safety, in that they use common methods for their analysis and may require input from each other.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] It can be said that a system must be reliably safe.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering focuses on the costs of failure caused by the system downtime, cost of spares, repair equipment, personnel, and cost of warranty claims.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The word *reliability* can be traced back to 1816 and is first attested to the poet Samuel Taylor Coleridge.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Before World War II the term was linked mostly to repeatability; a test (in any type of science) was considered "reliable" if the same results would be obtained repeatedly.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1920s, product improvement through the use of statistical process control was promoted by Dr.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Shewhart at Bell Labs, around the time that Waloddi Weibull was working on statistical models for fatigue.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The development of reliability engineering was here on a parallel path with quality.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The modern use of the word reliability was defined by the U.S. military in the 1940s, characterizing a product that would operate when expected and for a specified period.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In World War II, many reliability issues stemmed from the inherent unreliability of electronic equipment available at the time and from fatigue.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Miner published a seminal paper titled "Cumulative Damage in Fatigue" in an ASME journal.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] A main application for reliability engineering in the military was for the vacuum tube as used in radar systems and other electronics, for which reliability proved to be very problematic and costly.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The IEEE formed the Reliability Society in 1948.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In 1950, the United States Department of Defense formed a group called the "Advisory Group on the Reliability of Electronic Equipment" (AGREE) to investigate reliability methods for military equipment.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1960s, more emphasis was given to reliability testing on component and system levels.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The famous military standard MIL-STD-781 was created at that time.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Around this period also the much-used predecessor to military handbook 217 was published by RCA and was used for the prediction of failure rates of electronic components.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The emphasis on component reliability and empirical research (e.g.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] More pragmatic approaches, as used in the consumer industries, were being used.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In the 1980s, televisions were increasingly made up of solid-state semiconductors.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Automobiles rapidly increased their use of semiconductors with a variety of microcomputers under the hood and in the dash.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Large air conditioning systems developed electronic controllers, as did microwave ovens and a variety of other appliances.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Communications systems began to adopt electronics to replace older mechanical switching systems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Bellcore issued the first consumer prediction methodology for telecommunications, and SAE developed a similar document SAE870050 for automotive applications.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The nature of predictions evolved during the decade, and it became apparent that die complexity wasn't the only factor that determined failure rates for integrated circuits (ICs).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Kam Wong published a paper questioning the bathtub curve—see also reliability-centered maintenance.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] During this decade, the failure rate of many components dropped by a factor of 10.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Software became important to the reliability of systems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] By the 1990s, the pace of IC development was picking up.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Wider use of stand-alone microcomputers was common, and the PC market helped keep IC densities following Moore's law and doubling about every 18 months.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering was now changing as it moved towards understanding the physics of failure.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure rates for components kept dropping, but system-level issues became more prominent.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems thinking has become more and more important.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] For software, the CMM model (Capability Maturity Model) was developed, which gave a more qualitative approach to reliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] ISO 9000 added reliability measures to the design and development portion of certification.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The expansion of the World Wide Web created new challenges of security and trust.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The older problem of too little reliable information available had now been replaced by too much information of questionable value.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Consumer reliability problems could now be discussed online in real-time using data.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] New technologies such as micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS), handheld GPS, and hand-held devices that combine cell phones and computers all represent challenges to maintaining reliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Product development time continued to shorten through this decade and what had been done in three years was being done in 18 months.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] This meant that reliability tools and tasks had to be more closely tied to the development process itself.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In many ways, reliability has become part of everyday life and consumer expectations.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is the probability of a product performing its intended function under specified operating conditions in a manner that meets or exceeds customer expectations.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] To identify and correct the causes of failures that do occur despite the efforts to prevent them.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] To determine ways of coping with failures that do occur, if their causes have not been corrected.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] To apply methods for estimating the likely reliability of new designs, and for analysing reliability data.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason for the priority emphasis is that it is by far the most effective way of working, in terms of minimizing costs and generating reliable products.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The primary skills that are required, therefore, are the ability to understand and anticipate the possible causes of failures, and knowledge of how to prevent them.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] It is also necessary to know the methods that can be used for analyzing designs and data.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering for "complex systems" requires a different, more elaborate systems approach than for non-complex systems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] These analyses must be done properly and with much attention to detail to be effective.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Consistent with the creation of safety cases, for example per ARP4761, the goal of reliability assessments is to provide a robust set of qualitative and quantitative evidence that the use of a component or system will not be associated with unacceptable risk.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk here is the combination of probability and severity of the failure incident (scenario) occurring.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The severity can be looked at from a system safety or a system availability point of view.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability for safety can be thought of as a very different focus from reliability for system availability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Availability and safety can exist in dynamic tension as keeping a system too available can be unsafe.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Forcing an engineering system into a safe state too quickly can force false alarms that impede the availability of the system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In a *de minimis* definition, the severity of failures includes the cost of spare parts, man-hours, logistics, damage (secondary failures), and downtime of machines which may cause production loss.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] What is acceptable is determined by the managing authority or customers or the affected communities.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Residual risk is the risk that is left over after all reliability activities have finished, and includes the unidentified risk—and is therefore not completely quantifiable.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The complexity of the technical systems such as improvements of design and materials, planned inspections, fool-proof design, and backup redundancy decreases risk and increases the cost.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The risk can be decreased to ALARA (as low as reasonably achievable) or ALAPA (as low as practically achievable) levels.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Implementing a reliability program is not simply a software purchase; it is not just a checklist of items that must be completed that ensure one has reliable products and processes.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program is a complex learning and knowledge-based system unique to one's products and processes.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] It is supported by leadership, built on the skills that one develops within a team, integrated into business processes, and executed by following proven standard work practices.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is used to document exactly what "best practices" (tasks, methods, tools, analysis, and tests) are required for a particular (sub)system, as well as clarify customer requirements for reliability assessment.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] For large-scale complex systems, the reliability program plan should be a separate document.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Resource determination for manpower and budgets for testing and other tasks is critical for a successful program.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In general, the amount of work required for an effective program for complex systems is large.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan is essential for achieving high levels of reliability, testability, maintainability, and the resulting system availability, and is developed early during system development and refined over the system's life cycle.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] It specifies not only what the reliability engineer does, but also the tasks performed by other stakeholders.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] An effective reliability program plan must be approved by top program management, which is responsible for the allocation of sufficient resources for its implementation.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] A reliability program plan may also be used to evaluate and improve the availability of a system by the strategy of focusing on increasing testability & maintainability and not on reliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Improving maintainability is generally easier than improving reliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability estimates (repair rates) are also generally more accurate.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] However, because the uncertainties in the reliability estimates are in most cases very large, they are likely to dominate the availability calculation (prediction uncertainty problem), even when maintainability levels are very high.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] When reliability is not under control, more complicated issues may arise, like manpower (maintainers/customer service capability) shortages, spare part availability, logistic delays, lack of repair facilities, extensive retrofit and complex configuration management costs, and others.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The problem of unreliability may be increased also due to the "domino effect" of maintenance-induced failures after repairs.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Focusing only on maintainability is therefore not enough.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] If failures are prevented, none of the other issues are of any importance, and therefore reliability is generally regarded as the most important part of availability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability needs to be evaluated and improved related to both availability and the total cost of ownership (TCO) due to the cost of spare parts, maintenance man-hours, transport costs, storage costs, part obsolete risks, etc.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] But, as GM and Toyota have belatedly discovered, TCO also includes the downstream liability costs when reliability calculations have not sufficiently or accurately addressed customers' bodily risks.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Often a trade-off is needed between the two.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] There might be a maximum ratio between availability and cost of ownership.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The testability of a system should also be addressed in the plan, as this is the link between reliability and maintainability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintenance strategy can influence the reliability of a system (e.g., by preventive and/or predictive maintenance), although it can never bring it above the inherent reliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The reliability plan should clearly provide a strategy for availability control.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Whether only availability or also cost of ownership is more important depends on the use of the system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] A proper reliability plan should always address RAMT analysis in its total context.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] RAMT stands for reliability, availability, maintainability/maintenance, and testability in the context of the customer's needs.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] For any system, one of the first tasks of reliability engineering is to adequately specify the reliability and maintainability requirements allocated from the overall availability needs and, more importantly, derived from proper design failure analysis or preliminary prototype test results.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Clear requirements (able to be designed to) should constrain the designers from designing particular unreliable items/constructions/interfaces/systems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Setting only availability, reliability, testability, or maintainability targets (e.g., max. failure rates) is not appropriate.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] This is a broad misunderstanding about Reliability Requirements Engineering.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements address the system itself, including test and assessment requirements, and associated tasks and documentation.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability requirements are included in the appropriate system or subsystem requirements specifications, test plans, and contract statements.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The creation of proper lower-level requirements is critical.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The provision of only quantitative minimum targets (e.g., Mean Time Between Failure (MTBF) values or failure rates) is not sufficient for different reasons.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Compare this problem with the continuous (re-)balancing of, for example, lower-level-system mass requirements in the development of an aircraft, which is already often a big undertaking.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Notice that in this case, masses do only differ in terms of only some %, are not a function of time, and the data is non-probabilistic and available already in CAD models.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In the case of reliability, the levels of unreliability (failure rates) may change with factors of decades (multiples of 10) as a result of very minor deviations in design, process, or anything else.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The information is often not available without huge uncertainties within the development phase.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] This makes this allocation problem almost impossible to do in a useful, practical, valid manner that does not result in massive over- or under-specification.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] A pragmatic approach is therefore needed—for example: the use of general levels/classes of quantitative requirements depending only on severity of failure effects.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, the validation of results is a far more subjective task than any other type of requirement.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] (Quantitative) reliability parameters—in terms of MTBF—are by far the most uncertain design parameters in any design.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, reliability design requirements should drive a (system or part) design to incorporate features that prevent failures from occurring, or limit consequences from failure in the first place.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Not only would it aid in some predictions, this effort would keep from distracting the engineering effort into a kind of accounting work.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] A design requirement should be precise enough so that a designer can "design to" it and can also prove—through analysis or testing—that the requirement has been achieved, and, if possible, within some a stated confidence.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Any type of reliability requirement should be detailed and could be derived from failure analysis (Finite-Element Stress and Fatigue analysis, Reliability Hazard Analysis, FTA, FMEA, Human Factor Analysis, Functional Hazard Analysis, etc.) or any type of reliability testing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Also, requirements are needed for verification tests (e.g., required overload stresses) and test time needed.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] To derive these requirements in an effective manner, a systems engineering-based risk assessment and mitigation logic should be used.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Robust hazard log systems must be created that contain detailed information on why and how systems could or have failed.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Requirements are to be derived and tracked in this way.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] These practical design requirements shall drive the design and not be used only for verification purposes.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements (often design constraints) are in this way derived from failure analysis or preliminary tests.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding of this difference compared to only purely quantitative (logistic) requirement specification (e.g., Failure Rate / MTBF target) is paramount in the development of successful (complex) systems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The maintainability requirements address the costs of repairs as well as repair time.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Testability (not to be confused with test requirements) requirements provide the link between reliability and maintainability and should address detectability of failure modes (on a particular system level), isolation levels, and the creation of diagnostics (procedures).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] As indicated above, reliability engineers should also address requirements for various reliability tasks and documentation during system development, testing, production, and operation.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] These requirements are generally specified in the contract statement of work and depend on how much leeway the customer wishes to provide to the contractor.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability tasks include various analyses, planning, and failure reporting.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Task selection depends on the criticality of the system as well as cost.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] A safety-critical system may require a formal failure reporting and review process throughout development, whereas a non-critical system may rely on final test reports.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability program tasks are documented in reliability program standards, such as MIL-STD-785 and IEEE 1332.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Failure reporting analysis and corrective action systems are a common approach for product/process reliability monitoring.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] However, humans are also very good at detecting such failures, correcting them, and improvising when abnormal situations occur.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Therefore, policies that completely rule out human actions in design and production processes to improve reliability may not be effective.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Some tasks are better performed by humans and some are better performed by machines.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Furthermore, human errors in management; the organization of data and information; or the misuse or abuse of items, may also contribute to unreliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] This is the core reason why high levels of reliability for complex systems can only be achieved by following a robust systems engineering process with proper planning and execution of the validation and verification tasks.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] This also includes the careful organization of data and information sharing and creating a "reliability culture", in the same way, that having a "safety culture" is paramount in the development of safety-critical systems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] For existing systems, it is arguable that any attempt by a responsible program to correct the root cause of discovered failures may render the initial MTBF estimate invalid, as new assumptions (themselves subject to high error levels) of the effect of this correction must be made.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Another practical issue is the general unavailability of detailed failure data, with those available often featuring inconsistent filtering of failure (feedback) data, and ignoring statistical errors (which are very high for rare events like reliability related failures).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Very clear guidelines must be present to count and compare failures related to different type of root-causes (e.g. manufacturing-, maintenance-, transport-, system-induced or inherent design failures).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Comparing different types of causes may lead to incorrect estimations and incorrect business decisions about the focus of improvement.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] To perform a proper quantitative reliability prediction for systems may be difficult and very expensive if done by testing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] At the individual part-level, reliability results can often be obtained with comparatively high confidence, as testing of many sample parts might be possible using the available testing budget.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] However, these tests may lack validity at a system-level due to assumptions made at part-level testing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] These authors emphasized the importance of initial part- or system-level testing until failure, and to learn from such failures to improve the system or part.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The general conclusion is drawn that an accurate and absolute prediction – by either field-data comparison or testing – of reliability is in most cases not possible.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] An exception might be failures due to wear-out problems such as fatigue failures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In the introduction of MIL-STD-785 it is written that reliability prediction should be used with great caution, if not used solely for comparison in trade-off studies.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Design for Reliability (DfR) is a process that encompasses tools and procedures to ensure that a product meets its reliability requirements, under its use environment, for the duration of its lifetime.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is implemented in the design stage of a product to proactively improve product reliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] DfR is often used as part of an overall Design for Excellence (DfX) strategy.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability design begins with the development of a (system) model.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability and availability models use block diagrams and Fault Tree Analysis to provide a graphical means of evaluating the relationships between different parts of the system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] These models may incorporate predictions based on failure rates taken from historical data.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] While the (input data) predictions are often not accurate in an absolute sense, they are valuable to assess relative differences in design alternatives.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Maintainability parameters, for example Mean time to repair (MTTR), can also be used as inputs for such models.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The most important fundamental initiating causes and failure mechanisms are to be identified and analyzed with engineering tools.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] A diverse set of practical guidance as to performance and reliability should be provided to designers so that they can generate low-stressed designs and products that protect, or are protected against, damage and excessive wear.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Proper validation of input loads (requirements) may be needed, in addition to verification for reliability "performance" by testing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] One of the most important design techniques is redundancy.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] This means that if one part of the system fails, there is an alternate success path, such as a backup system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The reason why this is the ultimate design choice is related to the fact that high-confidence reliability evidence for new parts or systems is often not available, or is extremely expensive to obtain.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] By combining redundancy, together with a high level of failure monitoring, and the avoidance of common cause failures; even a system with relatively poor single-channel (part) reliability, can be made highly reliable at a system level (up to mission critical reliability).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] No testing of reliability has to be required for this.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Redundancy can also be applied in systems engineering by double checking requirements, data, designs, calculations, software, and tests to overcome systematic failures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Another effective way to deal with reliability issues is to perform analysis that predicts degradation, enabling the prevention of unscheduled downtime events / failures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] RCM (Reliability Centered Maintenance) programs can be used for this.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] For electronic assemblies, there has been an increasing shift towards a different approach called physics of failure.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] This technique relies on understanding the physical static and dynamic failure mechanisms.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The material or component can be re-designed to reduce the probability of failure and to make it more robust against such variations.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Another common design technique is component derating: i.e. selecting components whose specifications significantly exceed the expected stress levels, such as using heavier gauge electrical wire than might normally be specified for the expected electric current.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Results from these methods are presented during reviews of part or system design, and logistics.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is just one requirement among many for a complex part or system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Engineering trade-off studies are used to determine the optimum balance between reliability requirements and other constraints.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineers, whether using quantitative or qualitative methods to describe a failure or hazard, rely on language to pinpoint the risks and enable issues to be solved.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The language used must help create an orderly description of the function/item/system and its complex surrounding as it relates to the failure of these functions/items/systems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Systems engineering is very much about finding the correct words to describe the problem (and related risks), so that they can be readily solved via engineering solutions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Jack Ring said that a systems engineer's job is to "language the project." (Ring et al.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] 2000) For part/system failures, reliability engineers should concentrate more on the "why and how", rather that predicting "when".
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Understanding "why" a failure has occurred (e.g. due to over-stressed components or manufacturing issues) is far more likely to lead to improvement in the designs and processes used than quantifying "when" a failure is likely to occur (e.g. via determining MTBF).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] To do this, first the reliability hazards relating to the part/system need to be classified and ordered (based on some form of qualitative and quantitative logic if possible) to allow for more efficient assessment and eventual improvement.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] This is partly done in pure language and proposition logic, but also based on experience with similar items.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] This can for example be seen in descriptions of events in fault tree analysis, FMEA analysis, and hazard (tracking) logs.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In this sense language and proper grammar (part of qualitative analysis) plays an important role in reliability engineering, just like it does in safety engineering or in-general within systems engineering.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Correct use of language can also be key to identifying or reducing the risks of human error, which are often the root cause of many failures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] This can include proper instructions in maintenance manuals, operation manuals, emergency procedures, and others to prevent systematic human errors that may result in system failures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability modeling is the process of predicting or understanding the reliability of a component or system prior to its implementation.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Two types of analysis that are often used to model a complete system's availability behavior including effects from logistics issues like spare part provisioning, transport and manpower are fault tree analysis and reliability block diagrams.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] At a component level, the same types of analyses can be used together with others.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The input for the models can come from many sources including testing; prior operational experience; field data; as well as data handbooks from similar or related industries.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Regardless of source, all model input data must be used with great caution, as predictions are only valid in cases where the same product was used in the same context.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] As such, predictions are often only used to help compare alternatives.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is defined as the probability that a device will perform its intended function during a specified period of time under stated conditions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] where $f(x)\!$ is the failure probability density function and t is the length of the period of time (which is assumed to start from time zero).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability applies to a specified period of time.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In practical terms, this means that a system has a specified chance that it will operate without failure before time $T\!$ .
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability engineering ensures that components and materials will meet the requirements during the specified time.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Note that units other than time may sometimes be used (e.g.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability is restricted to operation under stated (or explicitly defined) conditions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] This constraint is necessary because it is impossible to design a system for unlimited conditions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] A Mars rover will have different specified conditions than a family car.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The operating environment must be addressed during design and testing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] That same rover may be required to operate in varying conditions requiring additional scrutiny.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Two notable references on reliability theory and its mathematical and statistical foundations are Barlow, R.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Often, knowledge of the statistical dependence between component failures is unknown or only partially constrained.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] When it is desired to model such incomplete knowledge, reliability theory allows for analyses that characterize ranges or bounds on system failure probabilities rather than unique distributions, particularly for small multi-component systems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Quantitative requirements are specified using reliability parameters.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The most common reliability parameter is the mean time to failure (MTTF), which can also be specified as the failure rate (this is expressed as a frequency or conditional probability density function (PDF)) or the number of failures during a given period.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] These parameters may be useful for higher system levels and systems that are operated frequently (i.e. vehicles, machinery, and electronic equipment).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Reliability increases as the MTTF increases.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The MTTF is usually specified in hours, but can also be used with other units of measurement, such as miles or cycles.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Using MTTF values on lower system levels can be very misleading, especially if they do not specify the associated Failures Modes and Mechanisms (The F in MTTF).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In other cases, reliability is specified as the probability of mission success.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] For example, reliability of a scheduled aircraft flight can be specified as a dimensionless probability or a percentage, as often used in system safety engineering.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] A special case of mission success is the single-shot device or system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] These are devices or systems that remain relatively dormant and only operate once.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Examples include automobile airbags, thermal batteries and missiles.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot reliability is specified as a probability of one-time success or is subsumed into a related parameter.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] Single-shot missile reliability may be specified as a requirement for the probability of a hit.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] For such systems, the probability of failure on demand (PFD) is the reliability measure – this is actually an "unavailability" number.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] The PFD is derived from failure rate (a frequency of occurrence) and mission time for non-repairable systems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] For repairable systems, it is obtained from failure rate, mean-time-to-repair (MTTR), and test interval.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] This measure may not be unique for a given system as this measure depends on the kind of demand.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In addition to system level requirements, reliability requirements may be specified for critical subsystems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p01] In most cases, reliability parameters are specified with appropriate statistical confidence intervals.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of **reliability testing** or **reliability verification** is to discover potential problems with the design as early as possible and, ultimately, provide confidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability of the product in all environments such as expected use, transportation, or storage during the specified lifespan should be considered.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability verification is also called reliability testing, which refers to the use of modeling, statistics, and other methods to evaluate the reliability of the product based on the product's life span and expected performance.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Most product on the market requires reliability testing, such as automotive, integrated circuit, heavy machinery used to mine nature resources, Aircraft auto software.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at several levels and there are different types of testing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Complex systems may be tested at component, circuit board, unit, assembly, subsystem and system levels.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] (The test level nomenclature varies among applications.) For example, performing environmental stress screening tests at lower levels, such as piece parts or small assemblies, catches problems before they cause failures at higher levels.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing proceeds during each level of integration through full-up system testing, developmental testing, and operational testing, thereby reducing program risk.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] However, testing does not mitigate unreliability risk.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] With each test both statistical type I and type II errors could be made, depending on sample size, test time, assumptions and the needed discrimination ratio.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] There is risk of incorrectly rejecting a good design (type I error) and the risk of incorrectly accepting a bad design (type II error).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] It is not always feasible to test all system requirements.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Some systems are prohibitively expensive to test; some failure modes may take years to observe; some complex interactions result in a huge number of possible test cases; and some tests require the use of limited test ranges or other resources.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, different approaches to testing can be used, such as (highly) accelerated life testing, design of experiments, and simulations.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired level of statistical confidence also plays a role in reliability testing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence is increased by increasing either the test time or the number of items tested.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test plans are designed to achieve the specified reliability at the specified confidence level with the minimum number of test units and test time.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Different test plans result in different levels of risk to the producer and consumer.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The desired reliability, statistical confidence, and risk levels for each side influence the ultimate test plan.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The customer and developer should agree in advance on how reliability requirements will be tested.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] A key aspect of reliability testing is to define "failure".
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Although this may seem obvious, there are many situations where it is not clear whether a failure is really the fault of the system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Variations in test conditions, operator differences, weather and unexpected situations create differences between the customer and the system developer.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] One strategy to address this issue is to use a scoring conference process.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] A scoring conference includes representatives from the customer, the developer, the test organization, the reliability organization, and sometimes independent observers.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The scoring conference process is defined in the statement of work.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Each test case is considered by the group and "scored" as a success or failure.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] This scoring is the official result used by the reliability engineer.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] As part of the requirements phase, the reliability engineer develops a test strategy with the customer.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The test strategy makes trade-offs between the needs of the reliability organization, which wants as much data as possible, and constraints such as cost, schedule and available resources.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Test plans and procedures are developed for each reliability test, and results are documented.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing is common in the Photonics industry.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Examples of reliability tests of lasers are life test and burn-in.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] These tests consist of the highly accelerated aging, under controlled conditions, of a group of lasers.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The data collected from these life tests are used to predict laser life expectancy under the intended operating characteristics.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The product life span can be split into four different for analysis.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Useful life is the estimated economic life of the product, which is defined as the time can be used before the cost of repair do not justify the continue use to the product.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Warranty life is the product should perform the function within the specified time period.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Design life is where during the design of the product, designer take into consideration on the life time of competitive product and customer desire and ensure that the product do not result in customer dissatisfaction.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability test requirements can follow from any analysis for which the first estimate of failure probability, failure mode or effect needs to be justified.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Evidence can be generated with some level of confidence by testing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] With software-based systems, the probability is a mix of software and hardware-based failures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Testing reliability requirements is problematic for several reasons.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] A single test is in most cases insufficient to generate enough statistical data.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Multiple tests or long-duration tests are usually very expensive.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Some tests are simply impractical, and environmental conditions can be hard to predict over a systems life-cycle.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is used to design a realistic and affordable test program that provides empirical evidence that the system meets its reliability requirements.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Statistical confidence levels are used to address some of these concerns.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] A certain parameter is expressed along with a corresponding confidence level: for example, an MTBF of 1000 hours at 90% confidence level.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] From this specification, the reliability engineer can, for example, design a test with explicit criteria for the number of hours and number of failures until the requirement is met or failed.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The combination of required reliability level and required confidence level greatly affects the development cost and the risk to both the customer and producer.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Care is needed to select the best combination of requirements—e.g. cost-effectiveness.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability testing may be performed at various levels, such as component, subsystem and system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems that must last many years, accelerated life tests may be needed.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] A systematic approach to reliability testing is to, first, determine reliability goal, then do tests that are linked to performance and determine the reliability of the product.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability verification test in modern industries should clearly determine how they relate to the product's overall reliability performance and how individual tests impact the warranty cost and customer satisfaction.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The purpose of accelerated life testing (ALT test) is to induce field failure in the laboratory at a much faster rate by providing a harsher, but nonetheless representative, environment.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] In such a test, the product is expected to fail in the lab just as it would have failed in the field—but in much less time.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability is a special aspect of reliability engineering.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] It focuses on foundations and techniques to make software more reliable, i.e., resilient to faults.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] System reliability, by definition, includes all parts of the system, including hardware, software, supporting infrastructure (including critical external interfaces), operators and procedures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Traditionally, reliability engineering focuses on critical hardware parts of the system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Since the widespread use of digital integrated circuit technology, software has become an increasingly critical part of most electronics and, hence, nearly all present day systems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Therefore, software reliability has gained prominence within the field of system reliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] There are significant differences, however, in how software and hardware behave.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Most hardware unreliability is the result of a component or material failure that results in the system not performing its intended function.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Repairing or replacing the hardware component restores the system to its original operating state.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] However, software does not fail in the same sense that hardware fails.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software unreliability is the result of unanticipated results of software operations.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Even relatively small software programs can have astronomically large combinations of inputs and states that are infeasible to exhaustively test.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Restoring software to its original state only works until the same combination of inputs and states results in the same unintended result.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering must take this into account.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] As with hardware, software reliability depends on good requirements, design and implementation.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Software reliability engineering relies heavily on a disciplined software engineering process to anticipate and design against unintended consequences.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] There is more overlap between software quality engineering and software reliability engineering than between hardware quality and reliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] A good software development plan is a key aspect of the software reliability program.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The software development plan describes the design and coding standards, peer reviews, unit tests, configuration management, software metrics and software models to be used during software development.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] In modern distributed and microservices-based systems, reliability considerations increasingly extend beyond component-level correctness to include the behavior of applications at the business-logic level.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] It addresses scenarios in which individual system components may appear operational, while failures arise from service interactions or logic errors, potentially leading to degraded user experience or incorrect outcomes.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Practices associated with application-level reliability include end-to-end observability, synthetic transaction testing, and validation of business-critical processes, complementing traditional infrastructure-focused reliability methods.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] A common reliability metric is the number of software faults per line of code (FLOC), usually expressed as faults per thousand lines of code.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric, along with software execution time, is key to most software reliability models and estimates.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The theory is that the software reliability increases as the number of faults (or fault density) decreases.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Establishing a direct connection between fault density and mean-time-between-failure is difficult, however, because of the way software faults are distributed in the code, their severity, and the probability of the combination of inputs necessary to encounter the fault.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Nevertheless, fault density serves as a useful indicator for the reliability engineer.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Other software metrics, such as complexity, are also used.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] This metric remains controversial, since changes in software development and verification practices can have dramatic impact on overall defect rates.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Software testing is an important aspect of software reliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Even the best software development process results in some software faults that are nearly undetectable until tested.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Software is tested at several levels, starting with individual units, through integration and full-up system testing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] All phases of testing, software faults are discovered, corrected, and re-tested.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability estimates are updated based on the fault density and other metrics.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] At a system level, mean-time-between-failure data can be collected and used to estimate reliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Unlike hardware, performing exactly the same test on exactly the same software configuration does not provide increased statistical confidence.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Instead, software reliability uses different metrics, such as code coverage.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The Software Engineering Institute's capability maturity model is a common means of assessing the overall software development process for reliability and quality purposes.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Structural reliability or the reliability of structures is the application of reliability theory to the behavior of structures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] It is used in both the design and maintenance of different types of structures including concrete and steel structures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] In structural reliability studies both loads and resistances are modeled as probabilistic variables.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Using this approach the probability of failure of a structure is calculated.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability for safety and reliability for availability are often closely related.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Lost availability of an engineering system can cost money.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] If a subway system is unavailable the subway operator will lose money for each hour the system is down.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The subway operator will lose more money if safety is compromised.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The definition of reliability is tied to a probability of not encountering a failure.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] A failure can cause loss of safety, loss of availability or both.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] It is undesirable to lose safety or availability in a critical system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is concerned with overall minimisation of failures that could lead to financial losses for the responsible entity, whereas safety engineering focuses on minimising a specific set of failure types that in general could lead to loss of life, injury or damage to equipment.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety engineering is often highly specific, relating only to certain tightly regulated industries, applications, or areas.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] It primarily focuses on system safety hazards that could lead to severe accidents including: loss of life; destruction of equipment; or environmental damage.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] As such, the related system functional reliability requirements are often extremely high.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Although it deals with unwanted failures in the same sense as reliability engineering, it, however, has less of a focus on direct costs, and is not concerned with post-failure repair actions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Another difference is the level of impact of failures on society, leading to a tendency for strict control by governments or regulatory bodies (e.g. nuclear, aerospace, defense, rail and oil industries).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Safety can be increased using a 2oo2 cross checked redundant system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Availability can be increased by using "1oo2" (1 out of 2) redundancy at a part or system level.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] If both redundant elements disagree the more permissive element will maximize availability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] A 1oo2 system should never be relied on for safety.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Fault-tolerant systems often rely on additional redundancy (e.g.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] 2oo3 voting logic) where multiple redundant elements must agree on a potentially unsafe action before it is performed.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] This increases both availability and safety at a system level.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] This is common practice in aerospace systems that need continued availability and do not have a fail-safe mode.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The above example of a 2oo3 fault tolerant system increases both mission reliability as well as safety.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] However, the "basic" reliability of the system will in this case still be lower than a non-redundant (1oo1) or 2oo2 system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Basic reliability engineering covers all failures, including those that might not result in system failure, but do result in additional cost due to: maintenance repair actions; logistics; spare parts etc.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] For example, replacement or repair of 1 faulty channel in a 2oo3 voting system, (the system is still operating, although with one failed channel it has actually become a 2oo2 system) is contributing to basic unreliability but not mission unreliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] As an example, the failure of the tail-light of an aircraft will not prevent the plane from flying (and so is not considered a mission failure), but it does need to be remedied (with a related cost, and so does contribute to the basic unreliability levels).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] When using fault tolerant (redundant) systems or systems that are equipped with protection functions, detectability of failures and avoidance of common cause failures becomes paramount for safe functioning and/or mission reliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality often focuses on manufacturing defects during the warranty phase.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability looks at the failure intensity over the whole life of a product or engineering system from commissioning to decommissioning.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma has its roots in statistical control in quality of manufacturing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineering is a specialty part of systems engineering.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The systems engineering process is a discovery process that is often unlike a manufacturing process.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] A manufacturing process is often focused on repetitive activities that achieve high quality outputs with minimum cost and time.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The everyday usage term "quality of a product" is loosely taken to mean its inherent degree of excellence.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] In industry, a more precise definition of quality as "conformance to requirements or specifications at the start of use" is used.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Assuming the final product specification adequately captures the original requirements and customer/system needs, the quality level can be measured as the fraction of product units shipped that meet specifications.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Manufactured goods quality often focuses on the number of warranty claims during the warranty period.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is a snapshot at the start of life through the warranty period and is related to the control of lower-level product specifications.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] This includes time-zero defects i.e. where manufacturing mistakes escaped final Quality Control.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] In theory the quality level might be described by a single fraction of defective products.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability, as a part of systems engineering, acts as more of an ongoing assessment of failure rates over many years.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Theoretically, all items will fail over an infinite period of time.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Defects that appear over time are referred to as reliability fallout.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] To describe reliability fallout a probability model that describes the fraction fallout over time is needed.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] This is known as the life distribution model.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of these reliability issues may be due to inherent design issues, which may exist even though the product conforms to specifications.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Even items that are produced perfectly will fail over time due to one or more failure mechanisms (e.g. due to human error or mechanical, electrical, and chemical factors).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] These reliability issues can also be influenced by acceptable levels of variation during initial production.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality and reliability are, therefore, related to manufacturing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability is more targeted towards clients who are focused on failures throughout the whole life of the product such as the military, airlines or railroads.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Items that do not conform to product specification will generally do worse in terms of reliability (having a lower MTTF), but this does not always have to be the case.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The full mathematical quantification (in statistical models) of this combined relation is in general very difficult or even practically impossible.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] In cases where manufacturing variances can be effectively reduced, six sigma tools have been shown to be useful to find optimal process solutions which can increase quality and reliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Six Sigma may also help to design products that are more robust to manufacturing induced failures and infant mortality defects in engineering systems and manufactured product.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] In contrast with Six Sigma, reliability engineering solutions are generally found by focusing on reliability testing and system design.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Furthermore, reliability engineering uses system-level solutions, like designing redundant and fault-tolerant systems for situations with high availability needs (see Reliability engineering vs Safety engineering above).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Note: A "defect" in six-sigma/quality literature is not the same as a "failure" (Field failure | e.g. fractured item) in reliability.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] A six-sigma/quality defect refers generally to non-conformance with a requirement (e.g. basic functionality or a key dimension).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Items can, however, fail over time, even if these requirements are all fulfilled.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Quality is generally not concerned with asking the crucial question "are the requirements actually correct?", whereas reliability is.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Once systems or parts are being produced, reliability engineering attempts to monitor, assess, and correct deficiencies.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Monitoring includes electronic and visual surveillance of critical parameters identified during the fault tree analysis design stage.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Data collection is highly dependent on the nature of the system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Most large organizations have quality control groups that collect failure data on vehicles, equipment and machinery.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Consumer product failures are often tracked by the number of returns.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] For systems in dormant storage or on standby, it is necessary to establish a formal surveillance program to inspect and test random samples.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Any changes to the system, such as field upgrades or recall repairs, require additional reliability testing to ensure the reliability of the modification.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Since it is not possible to anticipate all the failure modes of a given system, especially ones with a human element, failures will occur.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability program also includes a systematic root cause analysis that identifies the causal relationships involved in the failure such that effective corrective actions may be implemented.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] When possible, system failures and corrective actions are reported to the reliability engineering organization.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the most common methods to apply to a reliability operational assessment are failure reporting, analysis, and corrective action systems (FRACAS).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] This systematic approach develops a reliability, safety, and logistics assessment based on failure/incident reporting, management, analysis, and corrective/preventive actions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Organizations today are adopting this method and utilizing commercial systems (such as Web-based FRACAS applications) that enable them to create a failure/incident data repository from which statistics can be derived to view accurate and genuine reliability, safety, and quality metrics.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] It is extremely important for an organization to adopt a common FRACAS system for all end items.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Also, it should allow test results to be captured in a practical way.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Failure to adopt one easy-to-use (in terms of ease of data-entry for field engineers and repair shop engineers) and easy-to-maintain integrated system is likely to result in a failure of the FRACAS program itself.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Some of the common outputs from a FRACAS system include Field MTBF, MTTR, spares consumption, reliability growth, failure/incidents distribution by type, location, part no., serial no., and symptom.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The use of past data to predict the reliability of new comparable systems/items can be misleading as reliability is a function of the context of use and can be affected by small changes in design/manufacturing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Systems of any significant complexity are developed by organizations of people, such as a commercial company or a government agency.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The reliability engineering organization must be consistent with the company's organizational structure.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] For small, non-critical systems, reliability engineering may be informal.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] As complexity grows, the need arises for a formal reliability function.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability is important to the customer, the customer may even specify certain aspects of the reliability organization.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] There are several common types of reliability organizations.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] The project manager or chief engineer may employ one or more reliability engineers directly.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] In larger organizations, there is usually a product assurance or specialty engineering organization, which may include reliability, maintainability, quality, safety, human factors, logistics, etc.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] In such case, the reliability engineer reports to the product assurance manager or specialty engineering manager.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] In some cases, a company may wish to establish an independent reliability organization.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] This is desirable to ensure that the system reliability, which is often expensive and time-consuming, is not unduly slighted due to budget and schedule pressures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] In such cases, the reliability engineer works for the project day-to-day, but is actually employed and paid by a separate organization within the company.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Because reliability engineering is critical to early system design, it has become common for reliability engineers, however, the organization is structured, to work as part of an integrated product team.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Some universities offer graduate degrees in reliability engineering.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Other reliability professionals typically have an engineering, statistics, math, or physics degree from a university or college program.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Many engineering programs offer reliability courses, and some universities have entire reliability engineering programs.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] A reliability engineer must be registered as a professional engineer by the state or province by law, but not all reliability professionals are engineers.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Reliability engineers are required in systems where public safety is at risk.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] There are many professional conferences and industry training programs available for reliability engineers.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/reliability-engineering-p02] Several professional organizations exist for reliability engineers, including the American Society for Quality Reliability Division (ASQ-RD), the IEEE Reliability Society, the American Society for Quality (ASQ), and the Society of Reliability Engineers (SRE).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In science and reliability engineering, **root-cause analysis** (**RCA**) is a method of problem solving used for identifying the root causes of faults or problems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] It is widely used in IT operations, manufacturing, telecommunications, industrial process control, accident analysis (e.g., in aviation, rail transport, or nuclear plants), medical diagnosis, the healthcare industry (e.g., for epidemiology).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is a form of inductive inference (first create a theory, or *root*, based on empirical evidence, or *causes*) and deductive inference (test the theory, i.e., the underlying causal mechanisms, with empirical data).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Establish a causal graph between the root-cause and the problem.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA generally serves as input to a remediation process whereby corrective actions are taken to prevent the problem from recurring.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The name of this process varies between application domains.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] According to ISO/IEC 31010, RCA may include these techniques: five whys, failure mode and effects analysis (FMEA), fault tree analysis, Ishikawa diagrams, and Pareto analysis.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] There are essentially two ways of repairing faults and solving problems in science and engineering.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Reactive management consists of reacting quickly after the problem occurs, by treating the symptoms.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] This type of management is implemented by reactive systems, self-adaptive systems, self-organized systems, and complex adaptive systems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The goal here is to react quickly and alleviate the effects of the problem as soon as possible.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Proactive management, conversely, consists of preventing problems from occurring.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Many techniques can be used for this purpose, ranging from good practices in design to analyzing in detail problems that have already occurred and taking actions to make sure they never recur.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Speed is not as important here as the accuracy and precision of the diagnosis.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The focus is on addressing the real cause of the problem rather than its effects.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is often used in proactive management to identify the root cause of a problem, that is, the factor that was the leading cause.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] It is customary to refer to the "root cause" in singular form, but one or several factors may constitute the *root cause(s)* of the problem under study.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] A factor is considered the "root cause" of a problem if removing it prevents the problem from recurring.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Conversely, a "causal factor" is a contributing action that affects an incident/event's outcome but is not the root cause.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Although removing a causal factor can benefit an outcome, it does not prevent its recurrence with certainty.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] A great way to look at the proactive/reactive picture is to consider the Bowtie Risk Assessment model.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In the center of the model is the event or accident.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] To the left, are the anticipated hazards and the line of defenses put in place to prevent those hazards from causing events.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The line of defense is the regulatory requirements, applicable procedures, physical barriers, and cyber barriers that are in place to manage operations and prevent events.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] A great way to use root-cause analysis is to proactively evaluate the effectiveness of those defenses by comparing actual performance against applicable requirements, identifying performance gaps, and then closing the gaps to strengthen those defenses.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] If an event occurs, then we are on the right side of the model, the reactive side where the emphasis is on identifying the root causes and mitigating the damage.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Imagine an investigation into a machine that stopped because it was overloaded and the fuse blew.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Investigation shows that the machine was overloaded because it had a bearing that was not being sufficiently lubricated.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The investigation proceeds further and finds that the automatic lubrication mechanism had a pump that was not pumping sufficiently, hence the lack of lubrication.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Investigation of the pump shows that it has a worn shaft.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Investigation of why the shaft was worn discovers that there is not an adequate mechanism to prevent metal scrap getting into the pump; this enabled scrap to get into the pump and damage it.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The apparent root cause of the problem is that metal scrap can contaminate the lubrication system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Fixing this problem ought to prevent the whole sequence of events from recurring.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The *real* root cause could be a design issue if there is no filter to prevent the metal scrap getting into the system.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Or if it has a filter that was blocked due to a lack of routine inspection, then the *real* root cause is a maintenance issue.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Compare this with an investigation that does not find the root cause: replacing the fuse, the bearing, or the lubrication pump will probably allow the machine to go back into operation for a while.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] However, there is a risk that the problem will simply recur until the root cause is dealt with.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In general terms, for the investigating team, such as quality and engineering personnel, vernacularly speaking, it commonly takes around 5 times asking "why".
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The above example does not include cost/benefit analysis: does the cost of replacing one or more machines exceed the cost of downtime until the fuse is replaced?
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] This situation is sometimes referred to as *the cure being worse than the disease*.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] This can help explain the problem of the cure being worse than the disease.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Costs to consider go beyond finances when considering the personnel who operate the machinery.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Ultimately, the goal is to prevent downtime; but more so prevent catastrophic injuries.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Despite the different approaches among the various schools of root-cause analysis and the specifics of each application domain, RCA generally follows the same steps.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Effective problem statements and event descriptions (as failures, for example) are helpful and usually required to ensure the execution of appropriate root-cause analyses.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Problem statements are the North Star of the RCA as it keeps the team focused on what they are investigating and prevents them from going astray.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Most RCAs begin with a fact finding session to gather available information such as witness statements, the chronology of events and applicable requirements for the evolutions that were taking place at the time of the event.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The information can be used to establish a sequence of events or timeline for the event, and to identify the line of the defenses that should have prevented the event (i.e. the administrative requirements, and physical and cyber barriers).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Available databases should also be queried and analyzed (such as corrective action program and safety program databases), and data analysis tools such as Pareto charts, process maps, fault trees, and other tools that provide insights into performance gaps.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Any number of data analysis tools can be brought to bear, including data analysis tools from Lean Six Sigma, statistical analysis tools, and others such as hierarchical clustering and data-mining solutions (such as graph-theory-based data mining).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Another consists in comparing the situation under investigation with past situations stored in case libraries, using case-based reasoning tools and can include change analysis, comparative timeline analysis and task analysis.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] After identifying the defenses in place that should have prevented the event or accident, an analysis of defenses (traditionally called Barrier Analysis) can be conducted in every case, including non-RCA investigations.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] These initial gaps in performance are merely symptoms of deeper-seated causes.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] These symptomatic performance gaps are used to develop lines of inquiry questions as outlined below, to pursue the symptoms back to their points of origin (i.e. the root causes) using cause-and-effect analysis.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] After gathering available information, organizing it into charts with timelines and other data, after analyzing available data, and after conducting an analysis of defenses, those insights are used to generate questions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] These questions become lines of inquiry for cause-and-effect analysis.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] There should not be any curiosity questions, questions that reflect "confirmation bias" (i.e. asking a leading question so they answer what the RCA team thinks are the causes), or questions that are accusatory in nature that will cause those helping the investigation to close down and withdraw.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Once a robust set of lines of inquiry questions has been developed from the factual evidence collected, the applicable requirements, and an analysis of the available data, those questions can be taken to the organization's subject matter experts.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] This begins the process of cause-and-effect analysis.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Once a question is posed to the affected organization, their answer is used to pose a follow-up Socratic questions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Socratic questions keep the investigation flowing down to the next deeper causal factors until the organization runs out of answers, or the last causal factor is beyond the organization's control.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] There are many skills involved in conducting an effective cause-and-effect analysis, including facilitation skills, communication skills, and Socratic questioning.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] When conducted properly, this will take the RCA down to the deepest-seated root causes.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] A word of caution: Ishikawa or the Fishbone Diagram, and the 5-Whys methods, are not rigorous enough for conducting a root-cause analysis.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The Fishbone is from the 1940s and the 5-Whys is from the 1930, and there are much more advanced methods available.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Look for methods that were developed in this century (the year 2000 and later), as they are more likely to account for the new dynamics of the modern sociotechnical work environments.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The best way to chart the results of an RCA investigation is to start populating the final chart from the start.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] This process has become much easier with the advent of virtual whiteboards.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In a single virtual whiteboard, the timelines, lines of defenses, data analysis, lines of inquiry questions, cause-and-effect analysis, root causes, and corrective action plan can be displayed.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The Extent of Cause reviews are conducted to determine the extent of the damage or impact that the root causes and contributing factors had on humans, equipment, or facilities.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Extent of Cause reviews are an Achilles heel in the vast majority of organizations and a primary reason why RCAs and corrective action plans fail to prevent recurrence.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Also, care must be taken to avoid corrective action plans that simply add more administrative requirements and more training to the organization.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] To avoid this, use the Hierarchy of Hazard Controls and Lean Mistake Proofing as guidelines for developing effective corrective actions that have a much higher likelihood of preventing recurrence.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] After a pre-determined period after the implementation of the corrective action plan, an effectiveness review is scheduled to evaluate the effectiveness of those corrective actions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] This requires specifying a set of metrics or indicators that will be monitored prior to and after the corrective actions are implemented, so their impact can be measured.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] If the desired results are not achieved, which in most cases is a significant reduction in the magnitude or frequency of the event or problem, then the RCA must be reopened as it was not effective.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] To be effective, root-cause analysis must be performed systematically.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The process enables the chance to not miss any other important details.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] A team effort is typically required, and ideally all persons involved should arrive at the same conclusion.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In aircraft accident analyses, for example, the conclusions of the investigation and the root causes that are identified must be backed up by documented evidence.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The goal of RCA is to identify the root cause of the problem with the intent to stop the problem from recurring or worsening.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The next step is to trigger long-term corrective actions to address the root cause identified during RCA, and make sure that the problem does not resurface.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Correcting a problem is not formally part of RCA, however; these are different steps in a problem-solving process known as fault management in IT and telecommunications, repair in engineering, remediation in aviation, environmental remediation in ecology, therapy in medicine, etc.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is used in many application domains.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA is specifically called out in the United States Code of Federal Regulations in many of the Titles.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] TITLE 14 - AERONAUTICS AND SPACE >>> 14 CFR Chapter III, Subchapter C, Part 437, Subpart C, §437.73 Anomaly recording, reporting and implementation of corrective actions.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] A permittee must identify all root causes of each anomaly and implement all corrective actions for each anomaly.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] TITLE 21 - FOOD AND DRUG >>> 21 CFR Subpart J: 21CFR820.100(a) – Corr./Preventive Action: (A) Each manufacturer shall establish and maintain procedures for implementing corrective and preventive action.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] The example above illustrates how RCA can be used in manufacturing.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also routinely used in industrial process control, e.g. to control the production of chemicals (quality control).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also used for failure analysis in engineering and maintenance.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Root-cause analysis is frequently used in IT and telecommunications to detect the root causes of serious problems.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] For example, in the ITIL service management framework, the goal of incident management is to resume a faulty IT service as soon as possible (reactive management), whereas problem management deals with solving recurring problems for good by addressing their root causes (proactive management).
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Another example is the computer security incident management process, where root-cause analysis is often used to investigate security breaches.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also used in conjunction with business activity monitoring and complex event processing to analyze faults in business processes.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Its use in the IT industry cannot always be compared to its use in safety critical industries, since in normality the use of RCA in IT industry is *not* supported by pre-existing fault trees or other design specs.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Instead a mixture of debugging, event based detection and monitoring systems (where the services are individually modelled) is normally supporting the analysis.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Training and supporting tools like simulation or different in-depth runbooks for all expected scenarios do not exist, instead they are created after the fact based on issues seen as 'worthy'.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] As a result the analysis is often limited to those things that have monitoring/observation interfaces and not the actual planned/seen function with focus on verification of inputs and outputs.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Hence, the saying "there is no root cause" has become common in the IT industry.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In the domains of health and safety, RCA is routinely used in medicine (diagnosis) and epidemiology (e.g., to identify the source of an infectious disease), where causal inference methods often require both clinical and statistical expertise to make sense of the complexities of the processes.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA is used in environmental science (e.g., to analyze environmental disasters), accident analysis (aviation and rail industry), and occupational safety and health.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In the manufacture of medical devices, pharmaceuticals, food, and dietary supplements, root-cause analysis is a regulatory requirement.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] RCA is also used in change management, risk management, and systems analysis.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Without delving in the idiosyncrasies of specific problems, several general conditions can make RCA more difficult than it may appear at first sight.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] First, important information is often missing because it is generally not possible, in practice, to monitor everything and store all monitoring data for a long time.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Second, gathering data and evidence, and classifying them along a timeline of events to the final problem, can be nontrivial.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] In telecommunications, for instance, distributed monitoring systems typically manage between a million and a billion events per day.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Finding a few relevant events in such a mass of irrelevant events is asking to find the proverbial needle in a haystack.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Third, there may be more than one root cause for a given problem, and this multiplicity can make the causal graph very difficult to establish.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Fourth, causal graphs often have many levels, and root-cause analysis terminates at a level that is "root" to the eyes of the investigator.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Switching vendors may have been due to management's desire to save money, and a failure to consult with engineering staff on the implication of the change on maintenance procedures.
[src:failure-mode-effects-analysis/root-cause-analysis] Thus, while the "root cause" shown above may have prevented the quoted recurrence, it would not have prevented other – perhaps more severe – failures affecting other machines.
